docs.abstract: Her latest novel uses horror and a privileged white protagonist as vehicles for social critique.
docs.snippet: Her latest novel uses horror and a privileged white protagonist as vehicles for social critique.
docs.lead_paragraph: It is 1977. Hannah Jarrett, an attractive white woman in her late 30s, is living the American dream: a wealthy husband, two kids, a home in the Michigan suburbs, a Filipina nanny. She spends her days at country clubs and community relations forums. Her life has all the trappings of a Stepford Wife’s; “she has ceased thinking about how, why she is the person she is,” Joyce Carol Oates writes in her latest novel, “Babysitter.” “Her hive identity is secure.”

headline.main: Joyce Carol Oates’s ‘Babysitter’ Is a Serial Killer

docs.abstract: Eblis Álvarez’s albums are “collaborations” with fictional bands. His latest, with the imaginary El Grupo Renacimiento, is a psychedelic fever dream and a critique of technology’s encroachment.
docs.snippet: Eblis Álvarez’s albums are “collaborations” with fictional bands. His latest, with the imaginary El Grupo Renacimiento, is a psychedelic fever dream and a critique of technology’s encroachment.
docs.lead_paragraph: One day Artemio Morelia, a singer and maracas player for an obscure Colombian salsa band called Grupo Renacimiento, awoke and found himself transformed into a robot. Haunted by visions of HAL 9000, he was suddenly acutely aware of the coldness and the distractions of a constantly plugged-in world. “Memory is dying,” he sings on his band’s new single, “Metamorfosis.” “They’ve already connected the internet to my lung/to my heart.”

headline.main: The Meridian Brothers’ Eccentric Mastermind Is Electrifying Roots Salsa

docs.abstract: Since Coco Gauff went pro at 14, she has played under the weight of high expectations. Now 18, she has her own measures for greatness.
docs.snippet: Since Coco Gauff went pro at 14, she has played under the weight of high expectations. Now 18, she has her own measures for greatness.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Coco Gauff arrived in Paris in May for the French Open, she did not expect the tournament to be a milestone in her tennis career. It had already been a tough season: At its start, she flew across the globe to Australia, training and competing for four weeks, only to lose in the first round of the Australian Open. Not long before the French Open, she lost in the first round of a tournament on clay, the surface she would be playing on in Paris. Those kinds of early defeats were not what her fans anticipated from Gauff, who, three years earlier, at 15, proceeded, with astonishing grace and composure, to the fourth round of Wimbledon, defeating her idol Venus Williams along the way. Soon after that win, commentators seemed to be competing to hail Gauff’s promise. Chris Evert predicted she would win a Grand Slam championship, even at 18; John McEnroe declared that she would be No. 1. She was now on her fourth year of the tour, and although her skills were steadily improving, she had yet to meet those expectations.

headline.main: Can Coco Gauff the Tennis Prodigy Become a Tennis Legend?

docs.abstract: Wisconsin’s lieutenant governor embodies both the flaws and the promise of his generation.
docs.snippet: Wisconsin’s lieutenant governor embodies both the flaws and the promise of his generation.
docs.lead_paragraph: MILWAUKEE — Millennials came of age at a time of crisis. They are the first generation in American history positioned to be worse off than their parents, their economic trajectory forever altered by the economic meltdown of the late 2000s, as the ladders to the middle class were pulled up or broken by the crushing burden of student debt, the decline of unions and skyrocketing health care and housing costs, and as rapid technological changes proved more calamitous than democratizing.

headline.main: Meet Mandela Barnes, the 35-Year-Old Candidate Working to Oust Ron Johnson
headline.print_headline: Wisconsin May Send a Second Millennial to the Senate
